{"key":"processedPost-13352208","value":{"id":13352208,"first":13350754,"last":13355844,"when":1287425851,"utime":"10/18/10 09:17 PM","content":"A living room is not appropriate for mushroom culturing with a flow hood.<br /><br />The air from the flowhood is barely enough to bend a match flame over.&nbsp; Air currents in a large room can easily be stronger than that, thus they blow contaminants right into your media.&nbsp; In addition, you need to be wearing a surgical mask because your own breath is faster than the speed of the sterile airflow, resulting in bacteria contamination if you exhale or especially talk while making transfers.<br /><br />Put the flowhood in a small closed room, and let it run for at least an hour before beginning work.<br /><br />Culturing on agar from dry fruits is an advanced technique where even the experts fail a majority of the time.&nbsp; I'd suggest working with fresh sterile cultures or spores.&nbsp; Get an inoculating loop and flame it before use.&nbsp; Transfer the minimum amount of spores possible to each dish.<br />RR","title":"Re: query about laminar air flow","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}